<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-162-100  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 162 100.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic Engineering Times  March 13 1989 n529 p87(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Why SCS left minisupers. (Scientific Computer Systems Corp.)andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Costlow, Terry.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Scientific Computer Systems Corp (SCS) discontinues itsminisupercomputer program to focus on VectorNet, the 1.4Gbyte-seclocal area network for large computer systems that it introducedin 1988.andP;  The company cites the lagging market and pricing wars,and the need for venture capital, as the reasons forcing it toconcentrate on niche markets.andP;  Analyst Jeff Canin of Hambrecht andQuist says that SCS and its competitors all suffered from the glutin the market, which slowed the buyer's decision-making cycle andled to cost cutting.andP;  Other startup companies closing itsminisupercomputer operations include Cydrome Inc, Celerity andElxsi.andP;  Convex Computer Corp is one company that has continued togrow in the superminicomputer market.andP;  In 1989, its revenues grewto $105.6 million from $69.6 million the year before.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Scientific Computer Systems Corp. (products).andO;Topic:     Industry AnalysisMinisupercomputersFailure.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>